Notes


The normal optical depth &lt;U+03C4&gt; of a ring is the ratio of the total geometrical cross-section of the ring's particles to the square area of the ring. It assumes values from zero to infinity. A light beam passing normally through a ring will be attenuated by the factor e−&lt;U+03C4&gt;.116
The equivalent depth ED of a ring is defined as an integral of the normal optical depth across the ring. In other words ED=&lt;U+222B&gt;&lt;U+03C4&gt;dr, where r is radius.117
The equivalent depth of Galle and Lassel rings is a product of their width and the normal optical depth.
The corotation inclination resonance (CIR) of the order m between a moon on inclined orbit and a ring occurs if the pattern speed of the perturbing potential Ω (from a moon) equals the mean motion of the ring particles np. In other words the following condition should be met mΩ = npm = (m − 1)ns + Ω̇s, where Ω̇s and ns are the nodal precession rate and mean motion of the moon, respectively.118 CIR supports 2m stable cites along the ring.
The corotation eccentricity resonance (CER) of the order m between a moon on eccentric orbit and a ring occurs if the pattern speed of the perturbing potential Ω (from a moon) equals the mean motion of the ring particles np. In other words the following condition should be met mΩ = npm = (m − 1)ns + ω̇s, where ω̇s and ns are the apsidal precession rate and mean motion of the moon, respectively.119 CER supports m stable cites along the ring.
The longitude system is fixed as of 18 August 1989. The zero point corresponds to the zero meridian on Neptune.120
The forward-scattered light is the light scattered at a small angle relative to solar light. The back-scattered light is the light scattered at an angle close to 180&lt;U+00B0&gt; (in the back direction) relative to solar light. The scattering angle is close to 90&lt;U+00B0&gt; for the side-scattered light.


